\begin{HYPOTHESIS}
The failure of the linear regression model (R² ≈ 0) suggests that `dos_at_fermi` is governed by non-linear, discrete quantum mechanical interactions rather than continuous structural parameters. I hypothesize that the "Electronic Overperformance" identified in previous iterations is not a random residual, but a signature of specific "Symmetry-Composition Clusters" where the interaction between the transition metal's d-orbital occupancy and the crystal's point group symmetry creates localized electronic states. Instead of linear regression, I propose using an Unsupervised Manifold Learning approach (specifically t-SNE or UMAP) to project the high-dimensional feature space (including lattice parameters, space group, and elemental properties like electronegativity/atomic number) into a 2D latent space. By clustering these materials, we can identify "islands" of high-DOS density that are structurally distinct. We will then calculate the "Local Density of States Enhancement" (LDSE) factor—the ratio of a material's `dos_at_fermi` to the centroid mean of its respective cluster. Materials that exhibit high LDSE within clusters that are otherwise dominated by low-DOS materials represent "symmetry-protected electronic anomalies." This method will identify candidates that are not just outliers, but represent unique, optimized electronic configurations within their specific structural family, providing a more robust physical basis for superconductivity than simple residual analysis.
\end{HYPOTHESIS}

